We present the node-voltage method by utilizing the essential nodes of the circuit. Initially, we create a clean layout of the circuit to ensure no branches intersect and clearly mark the essential nodes on the circuit diagram, as depicted in Fig. 4.5. This circuit comprises three essential nodes $\left(n_{e}=3\right)$, necessitating two $\left(n_{e}-1\right)$ node-voltage equations to describe it. The subsequent step involves selecting one of the three essential nodes as the reference node. While the choice is theoretically arbitrary, practically, the most suitable reference node is often evident, such as the node with the most branches. The optimal reference node choice becomes apparent with experience using this method. In Fig. 4.5, the lower node, connecting the most branches, is chosen as the reference node and marked with the symbol $\boldsymbol{\nabla}$, as shown in Fig. 4.6.

Post-reference node selection, we define the node voltages on the circuit diagram. A node voltage is the voltage rise from the reference node to a nonreference node. For this circuit, we define two node voltages, denoted as $v_{1}$ and $v_{2}$ in Fig. 4.6.

We then proceed to formulate the node-voltage equations. This involves writing the current leaving each branch connected to a nonreference node as a function of the node voltages and summing these currents to zero, adhering to Kirchhoff's current law. For the circuit in Fig. 4.6, the current away from node 1 through the $1 \Omega$ resistor is the voltage drop across the resistor divided by its resistance (Ohm's law). The voltage drop in the direction of the current away from node 1 is $v_{1}-10$, thus the current in the $1 \Omega$ resistor is $\left(v_{1}-10\right) / 1$. Fig. 4.7 illustrates these observations, showing the $10 \mathrm{~V}-1 \Omega$ branch with the relevant voltages and current.

Applying similar reasoning, the current away from node 1 through the $5 \Omega$ resistor is $v_{1} / 5$, and through the $2 \Omega$ resistor is $\left(v_{1}-v_{2}\right) / 2$. The sum of the three currents leaving node 1 must equal zero, resulting in the node-voltage equation at node 1:

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{v_{1}-10}{1}+\frac{v_{1}}{5}+\frac{v_{1}-v_{2}}{2}=0 \tag{4.5}
\end{equation*}
$$

