Figure 4.7 $\triangle$ Computation of the branch current $i$.

The node-voltage equation at node 2 is:

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{v_{2}-v_{1}}{2}+\frac{v_{2}}{10}-2=0 \tag{4.6}
\end{equation*}
$$

Note that the first term in Eq. 4.6 represents the current away from node 2 through the $2 \Omega$ resistor, the second term is the current away from node 2 through the $10 \Omega$ resistor, and the third term is the current away from node 2 through the current source.

Equations 4.5 and 4.6 are the two simultaneous equations describing the circuit in Fig. 4.6 in terms of node voltages $v_{1}$ and $v_{2}$. Solving these equations yields:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& v_{1}=\frac{100}{11}=9.09 \mathrm{~V} \\
& v_{2}=\frac{120}{11}=10.91 \mathrm{~V}
\end{aligned}
$$

Once the node voltages are determined, all branch currents can be calculated. With these known, branch voltages and powers can also be calculated. Example 4.2 demonstrates the application of the node-voltage method.

#### Example 4.2 Applying the Node-Voltage Method

a) Utilize the node-voltage method to determine the branch currents $i_{\mathrm{a}}, i_{\mathrm{b}}$, and $i_{\mathrm{c}}$ in the circuit shown in Fig. 4.8.
b) Calculate the power associated with each source and specify whether the source is delivering or absorbing power.

#### Solution

a) We start by noting the circuit has two essential nodes, requiring a single node-voltage equation. We choose the lower node as the reference node and define the unknown node voltage as $v_{1}$. Fig. 4.9 illustrates these choices. Summing the currents away from node 1 results in the node-voltage equation:

$$
\frac{v_{1}-50}{5}+\frac{v_{1}}{10}+\frac{v_{1}}{40}-3=0
$$

Solving for $v_{1}$ gives:

$$
v_{1}=40 \mathrm{~V}
$$

Thus,

$$
\begin{gathered}
i_{\mathrm{a}}=\frac{50-40}{5}=2 \mathrm{~A} \\
i_{\mathrm{b}}=\frac{40}{10}=4 \mathrm{~A} \\
i_{\mathrm{c}}=\frac{40}{40}=1 \mathrm{~A}
\end{gathered}
$$

