The node-voltage method is streamlined when a voltage source stands alone between two pivotal nodes. Consider the circuit in Fig. 4.12 as an instance, where three pivotal nodes exist, necessitating two equations. One of these nodes is selected as the reference, and the others are labeled. The 100 V source, however, dictates a voltage of 100 V between node 1 and the reference node, leaving only one unknown voltage, $v_{2}$. Thus, the analysis involves a single equation at node 2:

$$
