Node-Voltage Analysis of the Amplifier Circuit

Let's apply the node-voltage method to analyze the circuit initially introduced in Section 2.5 and depicted in Fig. 4.16.

When the branch-current method was used in Section 2.5, the task involved solving six simultaneous equations. Here, we'll demonstrate how nodal analysis can simplify the process.

With four essential nodes in the circuit—nodes a and d connected by an independent voltage source and nodes b and c similarly connected—the problem reduces to finding one unknown node voltage. By selecting d as the reference node and combining nodes b and c into a supernode, the voltage drop across $R_{2}$ is labeled as $v_{\mathrm{b}}$, and the voltage drop across $R_{E}$ as $v_{\mathrm{c}}$, as shown in Fig. 4.17. Then:

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{v_{\mathrm{b}}}{R_{2}}+\frac{v_{\mathrm{b}}-V_{C C}}{R_{1}}+\frac{v_{\mathrm{c}}}{R_{E}}-\beta i_{B}=0 \tag{4.15}
\end{equation*}
$$

Both $v_{\mathrm{c}}$ and $i_{B}$ are then eliminated from Eq. 4.15 by noting that:

$$
\begin{align*}
& v_{\mathrm{c}}=\left(i_{B}+\beta i_{B}\right) R_{E}  \tag{4.16}\\
& v_{\mathrm{c}}=v_{\mathrm{b}}-V_{0} \tag{4.17}
\end{align*}
$$

Substituting Eqs. 4.16 and 4.17 into Eq. 4.15 results in:

$$
\begin{equation*}
v_{\mathrm{b}}\left[\frac{1}{R_{1}}+\frac{1}{R_{2}}+\frac{1}{(1+\beta) R_{E}}\right]=\frac{V_{C C}}{R_{1}}+\frac{V_{0}}{(1+\beta) R_{E}} . \tag{4.18}
\end{equation*}
$$

Solving Eq. 4.18 for $v_{\mathrm{b}}$ gives:

$$
\begin{equation*}
v_{\mathrm{b}}=\frac{V_{C C} R_{2}(1+\beta) R_{E}+V_{0} R_{1} R_{2}}{R_{1} R_{2}+(1+\beta) R_{E}\left(R_{1}+R_{2}\right)} \tag{4.19}
\end{equation*}
$$

Using the node-voltage method for this circuit reduces the problem from solving six simultaneous equations (see Problem 2.27) to solving three simultaneous equations. It should be verified that, when Eq. 4.19 is combined with Eqs. 4.16 and 4.17, the solution for $i_{B}$ matches Eq. 2.25. (See Problem 4.30.)

